    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Car's Total Cost</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Andrew Schultz letter on May 20 Count column holds calculation of costs of hybrid cars left out some benefits</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gasoline Prices Got You Down? Do the Hybrid Math'' (The Count, May 20):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Gasoline Prices Got You Down? Do the Hybrid Math'' (The Count, May 20):</p>
        <p>The article included figures that seem to show that hybrid cars are less economical than plain old internal-combustion vehicles at today's gasoline prices, considering the hybrids' initial higher cost.</p>
        <p>The calculation, however, leaves out the benefit to the planet, community health and the growth of a new economy that includes other sources of energy when more people ''pay more'' to drive hybrids.</p>
        <p>If you count only the direct economic consequences of driving, you keep getting the same results: more cars, more pollution, more dependence on fossil fuels. It's ''the tragedy of the commons'' -- the overuse of a commonly held resource -- and it has landed us in our current environmental and energy mess.</p>
        <p>The actions of the individual in society add up to a cumulative impact on the whole. Driving a hybrid isn't just about feeling good. One only has to smell the air near any freeway to know that the commons is real.</p>
        <p>Andrew Schultz  Rye, N.Y., May 23</p>
      </block>
